Cicero has for the most part merely put into the mouths of Roman speakers ideas which he has adapted from Greek writers. In the treatise Peri Philias (ÏÎµÏá½¶ ÏÎ¹Î»á½·Î±Ï) of Theophrastus, in the Lysis and also in the Theaetetus of Plato, in Bk. viii. of the Nicomachean Etltics of Aristotle, in the Memora- bilia of Socrates by Xenophon, and in some fragments of a philosopher named Chrysippus (fl. third century Bo), many similarities of thought and expression can be found, and there can be but little doubt that Cicero was acquainted with all these books, and, with them as a foundation, built up the edifice of his arguments in the De Amicitia. In Cicero's time a Roman writer was ashamed to show too close an acquaintance with Greek literature, and this, perhaps, is the reason why he does not mention his authorities as much as we should otherwise expect.
